    },
    {
      "id": "c054ded7125d865ff4e11e7768a7d62c026fce20",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 454,
        "name": "Artem Blagodarenko",
        "email": "ablagodarenko@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "ablagodarenko"
      },
      "date": "2020-08-26 15:18:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review\n\nDespite the fact the patch can be useful for filled and fragmented bitmap where _test_ operation mostly returns 1, it can make things slower for a quite empty partition, where (_test_+_set_) operation is faster then _test_ operation + _set_ operation.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0a336efff1e4261c69757c38b6714fd7c00a8016",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2020-08-27 02:01:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n> Despite the fact the patch can be useful for filled and fragmented\n > bitmap where _test_ operation mostly returns 1, it can make things\n > slower for a quite empty partition, where (_test_+_set_) operation\n > is faster then _test_ operation + _set_ operation.\n\nIn the case of an empty group, then it seems that test_and_set() would not be called as often as test_bit() would be called when the bitmap is more full (the common case), so that seems like the right tradeoff?  That makes the uncommon-but-fast case a bit slower, while making the common-but-slower case a bit faster...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "22571ebbf67520225fb5d9f05321bf1d18cdf9a5",
      "author": {
